title: Part 1
content:
Part 1

SOON, THE CHIME RANG.

The first thing Horikita noticed was their homeroom teacher's, Chabashira's, panicked and unusual demeanor.

After scanning the classroom, Chabashira's complexion quickly turned pale.

The abnormal change in Chabashira's demeanor caused concern among the students around her. Her eyes clearly lacked focus.

For several seconds, she said nothing, simply standing in front of the podium, looking over the classroom.

No, she wasn't looking—her gaze was unfocused.

Her eyes were lifeless, in some ways hollow.

Even the most insensitive person in the class would've likely had the same impression.

Initially intending to ask about the absent Ayanokouji, considering the atmosphere, Horikita judged that it wasn't at all a subject that would be appropriate to bring up, and she figured that checking on Chabashira's condition should undoubtedly be the top priority.

"Sensei, are you alright?"

But before Horikita could act, Hirata had already checked on Chabashira.

However, Chabashira did not respond to his voice.

It seemed Hirata's voice did not reach her.

The students, who had been relatively quiet, began to grow anxious at this abnormality.

"Um… Sensei?"

From the front seat, close to Chabashira, Kikuchi called out tentatively.

It was a call that came from point blank range.

But Chabashira did not respond, remaining motionless.

Kikuchi, trying to get noticed, stood up and waved their hand in front of her.

Finally, it seemed Kikuchi's actions caught her attention, and Chabashira glanced at them.

However, her gaze quickly shifted, now directed toward Horikita.

At least, that was what Horikita felt. Though, their eyes didn't actually meet.

It was just a vague look in Horikita's direction.

She concluded that Hirata's and the other students' voices weren't reaching her.

If that was the case, she might've been unwell.

There were no signs of anything going amiss until they headed for the opening ceremony, so they couldn't just leave it be. It might've been a medical emergency.

As Horikita pulled out her chair to stand and head toward the podium—

"I'm fine."

Had Chabashira been hearing the students all along, or had she only just now registered their voices?

Though lacking vigor, Chabashira murmured that short line.

"You say that, but you clearly seem unwell."

Though relieved to get a response, Hirata wanted confirmation.

"…That is… no, really, I'm fine. Just…"

Trying to continue, Chabashira leaned on the podium.

Her gaze turned toward Horikita again, but it wasn’t really focused on her—it was fixed on the only empty seat beside her, Ayanokouji’s seat. "Did something happen to Ayanokouji-kun?"

On the way back from the gym, if Ayanokouji had suffered a major injury or developed some kind of illness, Chabashira's change in demeanor would've made sense.

Was there something wrong? Such speculation seemed to have hit the mark somewhat.

Horikita's inquiry must've reached Chabashira for sure.

Yet, the lack of response and the ensuing silence suggested the seriousness of the matter.

"Is it an injury? Or an illness?"

Impatiently, Horikita asked the question, and Chabashira shook her head slightly from side to side.

This gesture indicated that their assumption was wrong.

If it isn't an injury or illness, then for now, it isn't an emergency.

But then, why's Chabashira showing such a gloomy expression?

"No, no, what is it? Something happened to Ayanokouji, right? Please tell us."

Despite reading the room, Ike, frustrated by Chabashira's vague demeanor, pressed for a quicker explanation.

Chabashira glanced at Ike before turning to look over the entire class.

Her expression remained grave, giving no sign of reassurance.

"…Honestly…"

Chabashira began to speak softly, but then she closed her eyes, and her mouth once came to a close.

However, she couldn't remain silent forever and raised her head.

"There’s something I need to tell all of you. This morning—no, just a little while ago—a certain student used their Private Points to exercise a certain right… or so it seems."

Though her words were hesitant and unclear, Chabashira told the class the truth.

"Huh? I don't really understand. What did they do with their Private Points?"

A certain student.

Used their Private Points to exercise a certain right.

Even as she tried to explain the situation, the details were so vague that it left everyone confused.

Is it a troublesome matter another class caused, something she can't elaborate on?

Speculations continued to grow in the students' minds.

"The student who’s absent from the classroom right now… Ayanokouji. He’s the one who exercised that right."

Chabashira spoke gravely, but her lack of clarity made the students tilt their heads.

What kind of right had Ayanokouji exercised?

"…Class… transfer."

Just as someone was about to ask another question, Chabashira uttered what seemed to be the crux of the matter.

Ayanokouji had transferred classes.

Indeed, Chabashira had mentioned a class transfer, but such a thing seemed impossible.

If he were to transfer from Class A, it would inevitably mean going to a lower class.

But that was a problem in itself.

"Um, Chabashira-sensei. If this is a joke, it isn't funny, and shouldn't you consider our feelings when we're listening so seriously?"

If it was as simple as just transferring classes as soon as you thought of doing so, no one would have a hard time with it.

However, a student would need to prepare twenty million Private Points to transfer to another class—a well-known fact and an unrealistic tale.

That was why some students began to take it as a joke.

"I also agree with Horikita-san's opinion. More importantly, are you really okay?"

Chabashira continued to make statements that not only lacked a sense of credibility, but the claims were bordering on contradictory.

Perhaps she was ill, or…

"Could it be that some special exam has started?"

Almost simultaneously with Horikita, Sudou crossed his arms and calmly expressed his thoughts.

Yes, from Chabashira's behavior and claims, it seemed more realistic to think that some strange exam had begun.

"I understand that what I'm saying is hard to grasp. However… it's the truth."

"Even if you say it's the truth—"

"Take out your phone and display the class OAA." Chabashira, refusing to admit it was a lie, gave instructions with her eyes lowered.

"I think you're taking this joke too far…"

However, a trace of unease crossed her mind.

By now, Horikita had begun to feel a slight sense of foreboding.

Many classmates, though skeptical, followed the instructions and turned on their phones.

They displayed the Class 3-A list.

Of course, it was supposed to list all thirty-seven students' OAA.

No, if it isn't listed, it must be a lie.

However…

Thinking she might've missed it, Horikita repeatedly swiped her screen up and down.

But Ayanokouji's name was nowhere to be found.

It was as if he had never been in the class, vanishing from the list.

Such an update to the OAA—she had seen this scenario a few times before.

It was the same when Katsuragi Kouhei transferred and when someone dropped out.

"Just now, it seems that Ayanokouji's data has been moved."

"What… What are you talking about, Sensei? That can't… that can't be right."

Horikita's voice unconsciously trembled.

"Ayanokouji has been transferred from this class to Class C as of today."

Chabashira clarified the situation's previously ambiguous details.

Ayanokouji had been absent since the opening ceremony because he had left this class.

"…Huh?"

She understood the words, Chabashira's explanation, but immediately after, Horikita's body showed signs that she didn't understand.

"What are you talking about…? Something like Ayanokouji-kun transferring to Class C…"

"That's not funny, Sensei. It's not April Fool's Day."

Many of the students still weren't even half convinced. They doubted it, assuming it was a lie.

"I also… don't like such jokes."

Thump, thump, thump—

"I think there's something off about Chabashira-sensei today."

Thump, thump, thump, thump, thump—

Please stop—

Horikita muttered in her mind.

Why is my heartbeat so fast, so loud?

In truth, she had understood why by this point, but she didn't want to.

Disturbed by Chabashira's bad joke, her mind was thrown into disarray.

"I feel the same way—it's unbelievable. But… this is undoubtedly the truth."

Thump, thump, thump, thump, thump, thump, thump—

"That can't be right. It must be some mistake."

As Horikita responded, she loaded the OAA list for Class 3-C.

If it's true that he's transferred, it'd be strange if Ayanokouji's name isn't displayed here.

But there's no way that could happen.

Yet, as she looked at the displayed OAA list—

Ayanokouji Kiyotaka's name had been added.

The moment she saw it, she became utterly confused, and Horikita's thoughts came to a halt.

"T-This is a lie, right, Sensei? That Ayanokouji-kun has transferred to Class C…"

Matsushita, who was clearly flustered, raised her voice in a way that was unlike her; some students couldn't hide their surprise at this unusual behavior.

"It's true… It's not a mistake."

Chabashira kept glancing back at the tablet.

If that was the case, it wouldn't be strange if there had been a notification from the school. It made her want to go against the flow of time and stop it.

Horikita's understanding of the situation hadn't caught up.

Ayanokouji had transferred classes.

No matter how many times she thought about it, it was incomprehensible.

It can't be possible.

Horikita and the others had finally, with a great amount of effort and time, climbed up from Class D.

And at last, they had reached Class A.

From that moment forth, for one year, everyone would unite to maintain that position.

Yet, there was no benefit to transferring to Class C.

"B-But what about the Private Points? Twenty million is a huge amount, even for him—"

"We don't know the details yet. However, since the school has officially approved it, he definitely prepared that amount."

"What? If that's true, then Ayanokouji… Eh, why?"

"No, it doesn't make sense, right? We finally managed to make it to Class A, right? And on our first day as Class A, he moves to the falling Class C—to the class that lost Sakayanagi?"

"What the hell is Ayanokouji thinking…? I can't understand it at all. Did you hear anything beforehand, Akito?"

"No, not a word… We’ve been a bit distant lately. If even Horikita and the others don't know, then probably no one does."

As it turned out, even the students within the group Ayanokouji was close to, such as Yukimura and Miyake, were not informed about this transfer.

"Or is that what this is about? Because he was dumped by Karuizawa and felt too embarrassed to stay in the class?"

"No, that can't be it, right? Even if he was embarrassed, he wouldn't have the funds to transfer."

"Maybe he begged people and ended up borrowing…? No, that's unlikely."

"Could he have betrayed us?"

"But then again, he didn't go to a higher class, he went to a lower one, right? It's just not normal… It's not like he's jumping on the winning horse, especially since Sakayanagi is gone. And it's not like Katsuragi's case where he no longer had a place to fit in and got pushed out, right?"

Shinohara muttered her doubts, to which Hondou responded with a similar suspicion.

There were things they couldn't even imagine.

Or rather, at least most students wouldn't even imagine it—

That Ayanokouji alone could influence the outcome of the class battles with his abilities.

There was a chance that Ayanokouji might've wanted to take it easy.

However, it could've been argued that staying in this class and doing nothing would be a far safer bet than transferring to a class that sank with Sakayanagi's departure.

"I don't know. It's weird to voluntarily go down to a lower class, but there might be Private Points involved. Not just the transfer funds, but getting paid for living expenses for the next year in return—"

"That’s even weirder. That would mean he’s being brought in as a replacement for Sakayanagi, or rather, someone worth paying a huge sum to guarantee Class C’s victory. But why Ayanokouji? Sure, he’s been making some noticeable moves lately, but…"

Upon hearing that, Horikita gasped.

Even if she didn't understand Ayanokouji's intentions, she couldn't discard the idea that the former Sakayanagi class had acted to acquire Ayanokouji. Rather, it might've been the most logical choice they could take to turn things around.

But that raised the question: Would Ayanokouji really agree to such a proposal?

"That's a possibility."

Kushida calmly murmured her comment amidst everyone's disturbance and confusion.

"But, you know—"

"Well, even if it's true… it doesn't feel like something to make such a big fuss about, right? It's not like Horikita or Hirata left."

"Kanji… Ayanokouji being gone isn't such a simple issue."

"You're saying that it's not that simple? Even if Ayanokouji-kun leaves, it's not even that big of a—"

Some students didn't see the reality of this transfer as much of an issue.

Kushida looked at them with a dismayed gaze.

"Ike-kun, Shinohara-san, sorry, but Ayanokouji-kun is much more important than you two think."

"Important, you say…"

"Just because it hasn’t come to light doesn’t mean he hasn’t contributed to the class in countless unseen ways. Right, Horikita-san?"

Kushida, remaining calm amidst the chaos, passed the question to Horikita, who nodded in agreement.

"Yes… Setting aside Ayanokouji-kun’s intentions, there’s no denying he’s the ideal recruit for Class C’s comeback. If he truly were someone we could afford to lose, Chabashira-sensei wouldn't be like this."

Rather than listening to her students, Chabashira remained in a state of shock.

Shinohara and Hondou exchanged glances as they watched her remain frozen in place.

"For real? Is it actually true?"

"Like Horikita said, Ayanokouji's presence is significant. If he weren't in our class, we most likely wouldn't be in Class A now. Of course, that's not the only reason we made it to Class A, but still… the hole he leaves is bigger than imagined—but still, why…"

Neither the teacher nor the students knew the answer.

If a student existed who understood everything in this situation—

Naturally, not only Horikita but many students' gazes turned to Karuizawa, who hadn't spoken a word.

Karuizawa, as a girlfriend, had spent more time with him than anyone else; she might know—

Everyone probably harbored such thoughts.

"Karuizawa-san, did he tell you anything?"

"…I don't know. I really don't know anything. It's not that I'm hiding anything; I truly don't know."

Without looking their way, Karuizawa answered indifferently. To Horikita, Karuizawa's clouded expression didn't seem to stem only from Ayanokouji's transfer, but also from Karuizawa believing that it was due to her, as his girlfriend, initiating the breakup.

No, that's not the issue now. Horikita dismissed such thoughts from her mind.

If Ayanokouji had truly transferred classes, that was the last of their concerns.

"Can this transfer be canceled if it's some kind of mistake?"

"If it's an illegal transfer, there's a possibility it could be canceled… However, in that case, the person who committed the fraud would face severe punishment. The arrows would also point at Ayanokouji."

An illegal transfer initiated by Ayanokouji.

It was an unthinkable possibility.

"But the possibility that it's a fraud is low. Since the school has officially accepted it…"

"Still, we don't know, do we? He might have some unexpected reasons that may come to light later, like him being threatened."

Otherwise, Horikita couldn't explain it.

A transfer to another class without any warning—there's just no way.

"No, that's…"

"Horikita-san."

Hirata's calm voice reached the flustered Horikita.

"I think we should start by accepting reality."

"Reality… what do you mean by that?"

"Just what it sounds like. He, Ayanokouji-kun, has transferred classes. This is an undeniable fact. The school has already accepted it, and his absence here is proof."

"But that's… that's not proof. He might just be sick, or it could be some sort of a mistake…"

"As Sensei explained, Ayanokouji-kun's transfer has been confirmed on the OAA. No matter how much we don't want to believe it, we have to start by accepting that."

Horikita was at a loss for words as Hirata continued speaking calmly.

Kushida, observing this, showed some slight interest.

"You seem quite calm, Hirata-kun. Whether it's a transfer or expulsion, a student may have disappeared from our class, and yet you're not disturbed."

Hirata had always been distressed whenever there was a risk of expulsion.

And after someone would leave, he was more concerned about the departed student than anyone else.

"Transfer and expulsion are different. Especially if it's his own decision. Besides, panicking won't help. No matter how much we fuss, Ayanokouji-kun won't come back."

"Isn't that wrong? Horikita-san hasn't given up on the possibility of it being a mistake yet. Shouldn't you be supporting her, like the Hirata-kun we know?"

While a few students in the class remained calm, Hirata was the most composed.

His careful observation of the class's reaction was uncharacteristic.

"So, what are you trying to say, Kushida?"

Sudou stood up, pulling his chair back.

He suspected that Kushida was stirring up trouble in the class again.

"Merely discussing this during our homeroom period without any clear information won't lead us to any conclusion. Right, Chabashira-sensei?"

With a signaling tilt of her head, Kushida glanced toward the hallway.

The other classes had apparently finished their homerooms, as the hallway was getting noisy.

"…Y-Yes, that's right."

The classroom was highly soundproof, so a normal speaking volume wouldn't carry to the hallway.

However, if someone were to approach the wall and get close to the door, it was possible to catch some voices.

Students with bad intentions might've been eavesdropping outside.

Sudou nodded appreciatively and sat back down.

"Let's end the homeroom period here. However, I ask that you don't take action against Ayanokouji for the sake of blaming or criticizing him. Currently, he hasn't done anything against the rules."

Just like the students, she had many doubts. However, as a teacher, she had to instruct them to refrain from any problematic behavior. As an adult, she mustn't forget to give warnings where necessary.

"I agree with Chabashira-sensei. Not only from a rules perspective, but also because approaching him in large numbers without understanding the situation can easily lead to trouble. I'll check on things first, so please stay calm until then."

"That's right. Avoid unnecessary contact with Ayanokouji, and make sure not to get into trouble with other classes. If anything happens, make sure to go through me or the school, okay?"

As a teacher, Chabashira thought that staying silent with the students any longer wouldn't help. She steeled herself, placing her hands firmly on the podium.
